Data collection options

Nnenna wants to answer the following question:

Should the company hire Deborah to do the job?

Choose the best way to collect data to answer this question.

Answer:

The best way to collect this data is:

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

Decide which will be the best way to answer this question.

STEP: Choose the most sensible method of data collection
[−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]
✘ a census
A census is when data is collected about every person in a country. For example, information about every person is needed when planning roads, parks, hospitals, schools transport, and big structures that affect every person.
✔ an interview
An interview (such as a job interview or a parent-teacher interview) is a formal or informal conversation between two or more people. An interview should have clear questions that can be answered in many ways. It can be done either in person, over the telephone, or on the computer.
✘ observations
Observations are the best method of collecting data when you need to look at behaviours.

Sometimes you need more than just a straight answer. An interview gives the opportunity for personal thoughts and emotions - this helps to explain the whole picture of a situation.

The tally chart you constructed should look something like the one below:

Each item is represented by a vertical or a diagonal stroke. We make 44 vertical strokes. Understanding data collection

Asking the right questions is an important part of the data handling process. If you don’t ask a good question at first, you won’t collect good answers.

7 Steps in Data Handling Process
1 Ask a good question
2 Decide how to collect data
3 Collect raw data
4 Organise the data
5 Represent (show) the data
6 Interpret (explain) the data
7 Answer, predict, and ask more

  1. If we need to know whether people feel safe at the community hall, here are two questions we could ask:

    Sandile's question is:
    Is the community hall secure?
    Zenzile's question is:
    I think there should be more money spent on community hall security, do you?
    Answer:

    The better question to ask is:

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

    Which question is neutral, clear, specific, not leading to one particular answer, but can be answered with a variety of clear answers?

    STEP: Compare the two questions
    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

    People should always be told why they are being asked questions, so that they:

    • are not afraid to answer truthfully, and
    • are not misled into answering in a certain way.

    Let's assume that people have been told that we need to know whether people feel safe at the community hall.

    NOTE: Neutral questions are good. Biased questions are not good.
    Neutral Questions: When a car is not in forward gear or reverse gear, we say it is in neutral. When a question is not strongly supporting something or strongly encouraging something, we say it is a neutral question. This is a good style of question because people feel free to choose their answer.
    Biased Questions: The word biased means unfair. Biased questions are those that one could think of as a car not in neutral but in forward gear or reverse gear. This is not a good style of question, because people feel persuaded to answer their question in a certain way.

    Sandile's question is neutral, clear, specific, and it can be answered with a variety of clear answers.

    ✔✔ Is the community hall secure?

    This is a good question to ask.

Classes & class intervals

A childcare facility has rules about how many adults are needed to look after the children. More adult help and care is required for younger children. To plan how many adults are needed each day, they need to know how many children in each age group they will be caring for.

Age in years Number of children
Younger than 11 year 1111
11 year or older but less than 22 years 99
22 years or older but less than 55 years 33
55 years or older but less than 1515 years 1212

Answer the following questions:

Answer:
  1. How many classes are listed?
  2. Are the class intervals all equal?
  3. For the third class, the class interval is year(s).
  4. If we added a child aged 88 years, this frequency would be added to .
one-of
type(string.nocase)
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 7 / 7 points left]

Count the number of age categories shown in the table. Do all the age categories cover the same number of years?

STEP: Look carefully at the rows in the table
[−2 points ⇒ 5 / 7 points left]
It is helpful to organise large amounts of data into categories called classes. The size of a class is called the class interval.

Each row (under the top heading) shows an age category called a class.

Class Age in years Number of children
1 Younger than 11 year 1111
2 11 year or older but less than 22 years 99
3 22 years or older but less than 55 years 33
4 55 years or older but less than 1515 years 1212

There are 44 classes.

STEP: Check the size of each class
[−2 points ⇒ 3 / 7 points left]

In the diagram, we can see that Class 44 (the children whose ages are 55 years and older but less than 1515 years) has a class interval of 1010 years.

For Class 44 we can say:

  • The size of the class is 1010 years.
  • The width of the class is 1010 years.
  • The class interval is 1010 years.

All of these statements mean the same thing.

The size of Class 44 is ten years but the size of Class 22 is one year, so the class intervals are not all equal.

NOTE: It is often sensible to have equal class intervals. But with data like age-specific physical ability, this development does not happen at the same rate each year. A child develops enormously between the age of one and two, but there is not the same degree of physical development between the age of nine and ten, for example. For this reason, the age categories here do not have the same class interval.
STEP: Determine the size of the third class
[−2 points ⇒ 1 / 7 points left]

Class 33 in the diagram above is children who are 22 years or older but less than 55 years, which means:

  1. Age 22 to age 33
  2. Age 33 to age 44
  3. Age 44 to age 55

So, this class spans a period of 33 years.

STEP: Check which class a person aged 88 years would fall into
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 7 points left]

If we added a child aged 88 years, this frequency would be added to Class 4.

Data handling terminology

Mrs. Modise teaches Natural Science. She gives her class a Periodic Table test. They have 2525 minutes to complete the test.

  1. What do we call the unsorted list of test scores?

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

    STEP: Recall the name for unsorted data
    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

    It is useful to use a 77 step process for dealing with data.

    This is Step 33 in the process:

    7 Steps in Data Handling Process
    1 Ask a good question Do the students understand this section?
    2 Decide how to collect data Set a test
    3 Collect raw data Mark and record test scores
    4 Organise the data
    5 Represent (show) the data
    6 Interpret (explain) the data
    7 Answer, predict, and ask more
    ✔ source data
    The word 'source' means origin. 'Source data' means information as it was originally sourced, not yet sorted in any way. Unsorted data can either be called source data or raw data - these terms have the same meaning.
    ✘ a histogram
    A histogram is a graph that shows the frequency of each group of data. Raw data must be sorted before it can be arranged into a histogram.
    ✘ a class interval
    When you sort data into category groups called classes, the range of each class is called a class interval. But we have been told that this list of test scores is unsorted.
    ✘ grouped data
    Grouped data is information that has been sorted into categories. These are called 'groups' or 'classes'.

Tally marks are a useful way to collect data. Short vertical lines are used to quickly mark items as you count them. When we add up all the tally marks, it tells us the frequency (how many times the event occurred). To make reading the tally marks easier, every fifth mark is written as a diagonal line followed by a space to separate each group of five. Here are some examples of correct tally markings:
33
44
55
88
1010
1212

In this case, the frequency of students who have pets at home = 88.

[−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]
✘ observations
Observations are the best method of collecting data when you need to look at behaviours.
✘ a census
A census is when data is collected about every person in a country. For example, information about every person is needed when planning roads, parks, hospitals, schools transport, and big structures that affect every person.
✔ a questionnaire
Questionnaires are the best method of collecting data when you want to collect responses from a group of people and you want to see general results. A questionnaire has a set of clear questions, usually with a choice of answers.

It is possible that a lot of people would need to be asked this question. It is quicker for lots of people to fill out a questionnaire, rather than to ask them one at a time.

So we should use a questionnaire to find out:

"What style of music do the students listen to?" Pop / Rap / Soul / Punk / Other

Summarizing numbers in tally charts

A tally chart provides a quick method of recording data as events happen. Here is an example of a tally chart for something that happened 88 times. There is 11 group of five and 33 individual strokes.

  • Individual strokes:

The tally chart you constructed should look something like the one below:

Each item is represented by a vertical or a diagonal stroke. We make 44 vertical strokes. Then every fifth observation is represented by a diagonal line crossing the previous four to make a five-barred gate. It's easier for our eyes to see 55 group(s) of five and 44 individual stroke(s) than if they where all vertical strokes. We can just multiply the number of groups of five by 55 and add the individual ones.

5×5+4=295×5+4=29

This gives you the frequency of 2929.

The correct answers are 55 groups of five and 44 individual strokes.

A survey can be conducted in many ways, for example: the survey questions can be asked in a personal or telephonic interview, or by using a written or electronic questionnaire.   1. Select the statement that is false about conducting a survey:

    Answer:
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

    One of the three statements is false. Which one?

    STEP: Read the statements and identify which is false
    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]
    A survey is a way of collecting data from a representative sample of people. A survey can be conducted in many ways, for example: the survey questions can be asked in a personal or telephonic interview, or by using a written or electronic questionnaire. A response is collected from each participant. Once all the data is collected, it is possible to look at the collected responses and make sense of what these results mean.

    These are both true statements:

    ✔ A survey is conducted in order to answer a question.
    ✔ Ask all participants the same survey question(s).

    This statement is false:

    ✘ Ask each participant the survey question(s) several times.

    This statement is false because you only need one response from each person, so you should not ask the person several times, or you would collect lots of one kind of answer. This would give you incorrect frequencies.

    This statement is false because a survey can be conducted in any language, provided the respondents understand the questions.

    [−0 points ⇒ 2 / 2 points left]

    STEP: Recall the name for unsorted data
    [−2 points ⇒ 0 / 2 points left]

    This is Step 33 in the process:

    7 Steps in Data Handling Process
    1 Ask a good question Do the students understand this section?
    2 Decide how to collect data Set a test
    3 Collect raw data Mark and record test scores
    4 Organise the data

    Grouped data is information that has been sorted into categories. These are called 'groups' or 'classes'.

Working with the mean

A group of 99 friends each have some marbles. They work out that the mean number of marbles they have is 66. Then 66 friends leave with an unknown number (xx) of marbles. The remaining 33 friends work out that the mean number of marbles they have left is 1717.

How many marbles (xx) were taken away from the group?

Answer:

The number of marbles taken away is .

numeric
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 3 / 3 points left]
Use the formula for the mean to figure out the total number of marbles in the original group.
STEP: Find the total number of marbles at the beginning
[−1 point ⇒ 2 / 3 points left]

We know that the mean number of marbles the group originally had was 66. Since there are 99 people in the group we can find the total number of marbles in the beginning using the formula for the mean:

meannumber ofmarbles (before)=(number ofmarbles (before))group size=mean×group size=(6)×(9)=54mean=(number ofmarbles (before))group sizenumber ofmarbles (before)=mean×group size=(6)×(9)=54
STEP: Find the total number of marbles after the 6 people leave
[−1 point ⇒ 1 / 3 points left]

We are then told that 66 people leave. After that, the mean number of marbles left is 1717. We can then find out how many marbles remain.

meannumber ofmarbles (after)=(number ofmarbles (after))group size=mean×group size=(17)×(3)=51mean=(number ofmarbles (after))group sizenumber ofmarbles (after)=mean×group size=(17)×(3)=51
STEP: Find the number of marbles taken from the group
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 3 points left]

Now we can work out the number of marbles which were taken from the original group.

number ofmarbles removed=items before−items after=(54)−(51)=3number ofmarbles removed=items before−items after=(54)−(51)=3

The correct answer is 33 marbles.
